				\begin{document}$Q>5\times10^{27}~\text{s}^{-1}$\end{document} is perhaps the most recognizable, as this is a stage that is most comparable to the plasma around previously visited comets like 1P/Halley. Here, traditional fluid-like plasma models can describe the interaction quite well on large scales, however many differences remain between this stage and the extremely active comets represented by 1P/Halley. Comet 67P was in this stage from approximately June 2016 to November 2016. The intermediately active stage for 1026<Q<5×1027s−1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
