				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$10^{27}\text{--}10^{28}~\text{s}^{-1}$\end{document} for a pure-water coma (which corresponds to conditions a few months around perihelion, see Heritier et al. 2018).

Photoelectron impact ionisation dominates over photo-ionisation in the optically thick part of the coma for large outgassing rates (Bhardwaj 2003). For a planetary atmosphere under hydrostatic equilibrium, the maximum photoelectron production rate occurs at the altitude where the optical depth reaches 1. In contrast, at comets with an expanding coma (not under hydrostatic equilibrium), the maximum production of photoelectrons occurs at an optical depth τ=2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
