				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\text{photons}\,\text{s}^{-1}\,\text{atom}^{-1}$\end{document}. Modelling the photodissociation of parent molecules (Sect. 2.1.1) allows the parent production rates to be derived. In addition, prompt emission following photodissociation can also contribute to the FUV emissions. While these photo-excited emissions depend only on the solar flux at the comet and not the plasma environment, it is necessary to understand them in order to identify the emissions that arise from electron excitation.

Unlike resonance scattering, dissociative electron impact excitation, as the name implies, dissociates and excites a neutral molecule. The energy of the impacting electron must be enough to break apart the target neutral and impart the remaining energy to raising the energy level of an atomic electron. This reliance on electrons above a certain energy, which is unique to each emission feature, closely relates the appearance of dissociative electron impact emissions to the plasma environment properties. However, the efficiency of this process changes with the increasing energy of the impacting electron, with maximum efficiency for UV transitions typically within 80–130eV\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$80\text{--}130~\text{eV}$\end{document} and declining thereafter. Proper treatment of dissociative electron impact emissions therefore requires careful calculation of the equivalent gX\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$g_{X}$\end{document} from the equation for resonance scattering. To do so requires knowledge both of the emission cross section, σ(E)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\sigma (E)$\end{document}, and the flux of energetic electrons, J(E,s)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
